## 2. Learning Model

What visual intelligence would actually need to learn, mapped onto the existing taxonomy rather than invented fresh:

| Learning | Existing taxonomy fit | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Color systems, typography | `personal_brand_signal` (closest existing `TaxonomyCategory` value) or a new value added to the existing 25-member enum | This is the one place a small, additive change to the taxonomy is genuinely warranted — see §5. Not a new domain; a new *category value* within the domain that already owns style learnings. |
| Layout/composition/information hierarchy preferences | `formatting`-adjacent — maps to the same conceptual slot as BrandOS's `format preference` (already mapped to `UserIntelligenceDomain` per the prior semantic analysis), and to `ArtifactPattern.sections` at the artifact-type level | No new category needed; existing structural-preference modeling already generalizes. |
| Motion personality, brand mood | `personal_brand_signal` | Soft, evolvable, low-stakes if wrong — fits the existing decay/confidence machinery for this category directly. |
| Accessibility preferences | `constraints_and_boundaries` | This is structurally a constraint, not a style — should never be modeled as a decaying `Learning` at all, the same reasoning Deliverable 8 (E1-2) already applied to workspace compliance requirements. |
| Component usage, design-system conformance | `WorkspaceIntelligenceDomain`'s `complianceConstraints`, parallel to declared text-style floors | Declared, non-decaying, workspace-scoped. |
| Illustration/photography style | `personal_brand_signal` | Same as motion/mood. |

There is no learning in this list that doesn't already have a home. The "complete learning model" the review asks for is: **the existing model, applied to a channel it doesn't currently extract from** — not a parallel model.

